## 6 Linear Alignment Methods for Finite Representation Sets

SSS 4 and 5 introduce ways of comparing language encoders as functions, which holistically characterizes relationships between them. We now address a more practical concern: Given two language encoders \(\bm{h}\) and \(\bm{g}\), how can we approximate their similarity in practice? Rather than comparing \(\bm{h}\left(\bm{y}\right):\Sigma^{*}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{D}\) with \(\bm{g}\left(\bm{y}\right):\Sigma^{*}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{D}\) over the entire \(\Sigma^{*}\),19 we compare them over a finite set of strings \(\mathcal{Y}=\{\bm{y}^{(n)}\}_{n=1}^{N}\). We combine \(\mathcal{Y}\)'s representations given by \(\bm{h}\) and \(\bm{g}\) into matrices \(\mathbf{H},\mathbf{G}\in\mathbb{R}^{N\times D}\), where we denote \(\mathbf{H}_{\bm{y}_{\cdot}}=\bm{h}\left(\bm{y}\right)\) and \(\mathbf{G}_{\bm{y}_{\cdot}}=\bm{g}\left(\bm{y}\right)\). We can approximate the notions of similarity from SS3 by optimizing over the affine maps \(\mathrm{Aff}(V)\) (for example, using gradient descent). Particularly, we approximate intrinsic similarity as

